article.description: New Mexico beat Wyoming on Tuesday night in a game marred by a major fight.
article.headline: Struggling New Mexico wins fight-marred contest
article.linkText: New Mexico beats Wyoming in game marred by brawl
article.story: ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- For a team on the ropes, New Mexico showed plenty of fight against the Wyoming Cowboys. The Lobos, trying to escape the Mountain West Conference cellar, beat the Cowboys 91-83 on the scoreboard Tuesday night. They also came out of a late-game brawl a little better off than the Cowboys. Wyoming guards Brandon Ewing, the leading scorer in the Mountain West Conference, and teammate Brad Jones, along with New Mexico guard Jamaal Smith, were ejected for fighting. The ejections carry an automatic one-game suspension for each player, which means the Cowboys will be without Ewing and Jones when they play at No. 17 Air Force on Saturday. Wyoming coach Steve McClain declined to comment on the fight after the game. He argued with a fan as he headed up The Pit's tunnel, then said as he neared the Wyoming locker room, "real class place this is." The game was halted for more than 15 minutes when the fight broke out beneath the Wyoming basket with 1:10 remaining in the game and New Mexico ahead 83-73. Aaron Johnson tied his season-high with 14 rebounds and Darren Prentice's 3-pointer started a second half scoring run by New Mexico that carried the struggling Lobos to the win. New Mexico (13-10, 2-6 MWC) won for only the second time in the last nine games as Johnson, who added 9 points, had his best game in conference play. "We're not going to give up," said New Mexico forward Tony Danridge. "We're going to keep playing hard and fight back into this race." It was a crucial win for the Lobos and McKay, the target of a growing wave of discontent among New Mexico fans, many of whom are calling for his firing. Wyoming (13-9, 4-4 MWC) got 21 points from Jones and James Spencer, but Ewing was held to a season-low 4 points. It was only the second time this season Ewing has failed to score in double figures. It was Ewing and Smith that started the brawl. The two ended up on the floor and as they struggled to get to their feet, made contact. As players from both teams converged, Jones shoved New Mexico guard J.R. Giddens. Smith threw a punch at Jones, then ended up on the floor again. With coaches, officials and other players trying to break it up, Smith got up and was pulled away by referee David Hall. Smith broke free from Hall and had to be restrained by McKay and assistant Brad Soucie. After order was restored the Cowboys got within six points at 89-83 with 22 seconds left. The Cowboys led through most of the first half but New Mexico took the lead for good on Prentice's 3 with 10:40 left. That snapped a 44-44 tie and kicked off a 12-3 run by the Lobos. After Cowboys center Bienvenu Songondo hit a free throw, Lobo Roman Martinez hit a shot inside and Johnson followed with a 3-point play. Jones hit a pair of free throws for the Cowboys and Giddens countered with an offensive rebound basket. Giddens beat the Cowboys to the rim to retrieve his missed free throw and rolled the ball over the front of the rim. Martinez closed out the run with a layup off a steal. Ewing found very few open shots against New Mexico's trapping and switching defense. He finished 2-of-12 from the field, 0-of-5 on 3-pointers. An 80 percent free throw shooter, Ewing was 0-for-3 at the line. "The guards defended him well, that's what happened," said Danridge. Reserve Ryan Kersten scored 20 points for New Mexico and hit 14 of 16 free throws, while Prentice scored 12 points. It was Prentice's ballhandling and passes to open teammates that kept New Mexico's offense in sync much of the night. New Mexico hit 36 of 50 free throws to Wyoming's 21-of-32 in a game in which 57 fouls were called. McClain said he felt the game turned in New Mexico's favor in the second half, when New Mexico shot 39 free throws and made 29 of them. Wyoming shot 29 free throws in the second half. "Anybody that was watching the game saw it change," McClain said. "We do one thing. We drive to the rim and get fouled. And we didn't see any of those [calls]."
